Dear Participants,

We are delighted to present our project, "Anyone Can AI," developed as part of the Google x Kaggle GenAI-intensive program. This initiative aims to demystify generative AI by offering an interactive learning experience with GPT-2, making foundational AI concepts accessible to everyone.

Our interactive tool provides a comprehensive, step-by-step walkthrough of how GPT-2 functions‚Äîfrom processing user input to predicting subsequent words. Users can pause at any stage to explore the intricacies of each step and engage with an integrated chatbot for additional insights. This resource is designed to deepen your understanding of generative AI in an intuitive and engaging way.

How You Can Engage:

Join the Conversation: Connect with us and share your thoughts on our dedicated Discord channel: https://discord.gg/2GEJdyJu
Participate in Live Sessions: Attend live demonstrations, preview features, and provide your valuable feedback.
This project is part of a broader community-driven initiative by Chiac AI, committed to empowering individuals to develop AI skills, irrespective of their background or experience. We invite you to be a part of this collaborative journey as we explore the exciting possibilities of AI together.

Hi everyone! I‚Äôm Jeff Stark. I gave a brief intro at the start of the course, but now that we‚Äôre wrapping up, I wanted to share more about my journey.
¬†
I've been fascinated by AI since reading *G√∂del, Escher, Bach* by Douglas Hofstadter back in high school. After 20 years as a software engineer, I‚Äôve decided to fully pursue my passion for AI and explore how to transition my career into this incredible field.
¬†
Over the past several months, I‚Äôve been immersing myself in AI through various courses and books. Here are a few that have been particularly impactful on my learning journey:
¬†
¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† ‚ÄòA Brief History of Intelligence‚Äô by Max Bennet, which brilliantly explores how our understanding of biological intelligence has informed AI development.
¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† ‚ÄòWhy Machines Learn‚Äô by Anil Ananthaswamy, which offers a mathematically rich history of neural networks and provides the best explanation of Bayes's Theorem I‚Äôve encountered.
¬∑¬†¬†¬†¬†¬† ‚ÄòChatGPT and the Future of AI*‚Äôby Terrence J. Sejnowski, which features a fascinating chapter on high- and low-dimensional spaces in AI models‚Äîperfect for grasping why performance improves with more parameters.
¬†
I‚Äôve thoroughly enjoyed and learned a lot from this course. I‚Äôd love to stay connected‚Äîfeel free to reach out on LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/in/jeff-stark-363331b1/ .
